data:
The Transfer of Knowledge in International Internship project of Hiiumaa Vocational School helps carry out the main functions, teaching concepts and internationalisation strategy of the school, as described in its development plan.
The main objective of the school: Hiiumaa Vocational School is a well-known and prestigious school in a manor house that provides high-quality education to all its students.
The main objectives of the project are:
1. To ensure high quality vocational education and efficient study arrangements
2. To offer varied study options for target groups
3. To provide richer specialised education through international practical training and work culture
4. To develop the system of practical training in companies in cooperation with employers
5. To encourage vocational teachers to work and study in and cooperate with companies to improve the quality of education they provide

The project will help develop and maintain our network of foreign companies and schools, so our school will have, by 2020, mutually supportive cooperation relations involving each group of subjects and the exchange of knowledge and experience with foreign partners will be a natural part of vocational studies at our school.

This project involves continued cooperation with the Hå gamle prestegard art and culture centre in Norway, the Great Yarmouth Preservation Trust in Great Britain, Edudelta vocational education centre in the Netherlands and Ronneby Port in Sweden.
New partners will include Coleshill Organics, an organic market garden in Great Britain; Tricase Port in Italy; Handverksskolen, a school of traditional construction in Norway; and Litorina educational centre in Sweden. 

The project will focus on high-quality practical training in companies, which is very important for learning outcomes and professional qualification.  The activities will be conducted in cooperation with the development manager and lead teachers. Lead teachers will be involved in preparations involving the learning mobility of our students as well as the related monitoring, feedback, analysis and making use of the results.
The project is meant for 145 vocational students. From our school, the project involves 26 students and graduates of the following professions: florist, landscaper, junior gardener, log house builder, stone building restorer, and small-port specialist.
The learning mobility of these 26 students and graduates, three lead teachers and the head of in service training will take place in the 2018/2019 academic year. Hiiumaa Vocational School will welcome three professional practitioners who will teach restoration, traditional building and truck driver courses in 2018/2019. Involvement of foreign lecturers is a significant addition to vocational training and an indication of high quality.

After the completion of their learning mobility, the students have acquired professional competencies to be competitive in the labour market in the following:
1. florists in making flower arrangements;
2. junior gardeners in organic vegetable cultivation;
3. landscapers in green area creation and maintenance;
4. log house builders in making and erecting log structures;
5. stone building restorers in the restoration of buildings;
6. small-port specialists in port management.
The students involved in learning mobility will:
1. make use of the practical training in the company to attain the required learning outcomes and professional qualification;
2. acquire professional competencies to be competitive in the labour market;
3. test their new knowledge and skills internationally and analyse the results;
4. acquire social competencies to work in multicultural environment;
5. be proficient in foreign languages.

The lead teachers will make use of the knowledge and skills they acquire in teaching the courses of floristry, gardening and landscaping by:
1. teaching the same modules in which the learning mobility outcomes are described;
2. developing the curricula, adding electives and making changes to teaching plans where necessary;
3. continuing international cooperation with the host companies and institutions;
4. cooperating with Estonian companies and being practical training supervisors.

Jane Üksik, the head of continuing vocational training, will make use of the new knowledge and skills in managing vocational training processes as well as in developing and marketing training packages for courses conducted at Suuremõisa manor house.
The learning mobility will add value to the vocational education of the students of and graduates from Hiiumaa Vocational School. Practical training in actual settings is pivotal for students. The more experience they have with different companies the better they are prepared for work life and the wider their horizon. The opportunity to work abroad in foreign culture and language settings provides a challenge for each participant as well as an opportunity for both personal and professional development.
